WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.362
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:06.362 --> 00:00:08.070
NADIM SAAD: Thank you,
Rob, and thank you

00:00:08.070 --> 00:00:10.950
all for coming here
today and for taking

00:00:10.950 --> 00:00:14.430
an hour of your busy schedules.

00:00:14.430 --> 00:00:18.254
Reality is five years ago,
I would have never wasted

00:00:18.254 --> 00:00:19.920
an hour of my time
attending a parenting

00:00:19.920 --> 00:00:26.130
presentation because I parented
the way my parents did,

00:00:26.130 --> 00:00:27.660
quite strict.

00:00:27.660 --> 00:00:29.730
But I thought I turned
out OK, so why would

00:00:29.730 --> 00:00:31.770
I do things differently.

00:00:31.770 --> 00:00:34.920
Until one day an
event at home actually

00:00:34.920 --> 00:00:38.440
made me really wonder if
I was doing things right.

00:00:38.440 --> 00:00:40.320
So it was a Saturday.

00:00:40.320 --> 00:00:42.120
My four and a half year
old daughter, Noor,

00:00:42.120 --> 00:00:44.740
was serving herself some salad.

00:00:44.740 --> 00:00:48.070
She dropped a salad
leaf on the table.

00:00:48.070 --> 00:00:51.330
I just asked nicely, oh, Noor,
could you please pick this up.

00:00:51.330 --> 00:00:53.340
She ignored me.

00:00:53.340 --> 00:00:57.660
I said Noor, you dropped a
salad leaf, please pick it up.

00:00:57.660 --> 00:00:59.760
She ignored me.

00:00:59.760 --> 00:01:03.540
Then I used my default method
at the time, my technique

00:01:03.540 --> 00:01:07.170
to get my children to do things
which was counting to three.

00:01:07.170 --> 00:01:08.620
Anyone else count to three?

00:01:08.620 --> 00:01:10.170
Show of hands?

00:01:10.170 --> 00:01:12.930
Usually about 90% so
the rest are probably--

00:01:12.930 --> 00:01:16.452
And I went OK, Noor,
I'm counting to three.

00:01:16.452 --> 00:01:18.681
I said one.

00:01:18.681 --> 00:01:20.340
Ignored me.

00:01:20.340 --> 00:01:22.250
I said two.

00:01:22.250 --> 00:01:23.500
Ignored me again.

00:01:23.500 --> 00:01:27.230
I went, Noor, you don't want
me to get to three, do you?

00:01:27.230 --> 00:01:28.321
Two and a half.

00:01:28.321 --> 00:01:31.090
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:31.090 --> 00:01:33.390
Two and three-quarters.

00:01:33.390 --> 00:01:35.040
And then I got to three.

00:01:35.040 --> 00:01:39.120
And the reality is I had no
idea what I was going to do.

00:01:39.120 --> 00:01:41.640
The only thing I
knew was my authority

00:01:41.640 --> 00:01:44.310
was based on that and the
fear of getting to three.

00:01:44.310 --> 00:01:47.550
And it used to work so well
and suddenly it didn't.

00:01:47.550 --> 00:01:50.560
Unfortunately I did not
react the best way possible.

00:01:50.560 --> 00:01:52.800
I actually started
screaming and shouting.

00:01:52.800 --> 00:01:56.460
And I pulled her up,
put her in her room.

00:01:56.460 --> 00:01:59.220
Lecturing her, how dare
you let me get to three.

00:01:59.220 --> 00:02:01.430
Do you realize what that means?

00:02:01.430 --> 00:02:04.410
But I realized that day that
actually my whole authority

00:02:04.410 --> 00:02:07.500
was based out of the fear
that my children had.

00:02:07.500 --> 00:02:09.000
And they were doing
this out of fear

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:11.500
so I was really
managing my fear.

00:02:11.500 --> 00:02:14.250
And that's what I'm going
to talk to you about today

00:02:14.250 --> 00:02:17.430
and how much parallels there
are between leadership skills

00:02:17.430 --> 00:02:20.510
and parenting skills.

00:02:20.510 --> 00:02:23.500
So the outline for today
is actually explain to you

00:02:23.500 --> 00:02:27.370
how I learned that parenting
skills can be improved.

00:02:27.370 --> 00:02:29.470
Then I'm going to talk to
you about what parenting

00:02:29.470 --> 00:02:32.460
and leadership have in common.

00:02:32.460 --> 00:02:34.210
Then we're going to
actually work together

00:02:34.210 --> 00:02:37.900
on defining what the key
leadership skills are.

00:02:37.900 --> 00:02:39.880
And finally, I'll
show you how to apply

00:02:39.880 --> 00:02:41.680
some of these workplace
skills at home.

00:02:41.680 --> 00:02:44.110
So I'll share with you
five very effective tools

00:02:44.110 --> 00:02:47.890
to replace the typical
basically, well, the one, two,

00:02:47.890 --> 00:02:52.030
three, the parenting by fear or
parenting by rewards actually,

00:02:52.030 --> 00:02:54.550
because it's the carrot
and stick approach.

00:02:54.550 --> 00:02:56.177
My objective here
today is really

00:02:56.177 --> 00:02:57.760
to give you alternatives
to the carrot

00:02:57.760 --> 00:03:01.630
and stick approach that are
so ingrained in our culture.

00:03:01.630 --> 00:03:03.700
Because it's all
about usually rewards,

00:03:03.700 --> 00:03:06.950
punishment, threats, and
management basically by fear

00:03:06.950 --> 00:03:08.060
or rewards.

00:03:08.060 --> 00:03:12.850
So hopefully you'll leave here
with an alternative to that.

00:03:12.850 --> 00:03:14.080
So how did it all start?

00:03:14.080 --> 00:03:17.080
Well, I already explained,
I was a stricter parent.

00:03:17.080 --> 00:03:20.350
And my wife was actually a
lot more, let's say, lenient.

00:03:20.350 --> 00:03:23.315
I sometimes say permissive
although she doesn't like it.

00:03:23.315 --> 00:03:25.440
And so that's how our daily
interactions look like.

00:03:30.260 --> 00:03:35.380
And the problem is actually
the more, the harsher I was

00:03:35.380 --> 00:03:36.840
and the kinder she was.

00:03:36.840 --> 00:03:40.430
So I had, I had clearly
had the bad cop role,

00:03:40.430 --> 00:03:41.570
she had the good cop role.

00:03:41.570 --> 00:03:44.510
Anyone else experience
this at home?

00:03:44.510 --> 00:03:45.830
Yeah, about 60%.

00:03:45.830 --> 00:03:48.500
Well, actually it's-- the
research shows that it's 75%

00:03:48.500 --> 00:03:52.100
of parents argue
about how to parent.

00:03:52.100 --> 00:03:54.290
And more than 50%
of these arguments

00:03:54.290 --> 00:03:56.390
are about how to
discipline children.

00:03:56.390 --> 00:03:58.760
So that's what we
experience on a daily basis.

00:03:58.760 --> 00:04:01.430
And it was, I mean it almost
got to break point, particularly

00:04:01.430 --> 00:04:05.940
after the incident, the salad
leaf incident that I mentioned.

00:04:05.940 --> 00:04:11.180
And thankfully, my wife
reacted very well to that.

00:04:11.180 --> 00:04:14.370
And she actually started looking
for things she could do better.

00:04:14.370 --> 00:04:17.149
So she stopped blaming me
for being the strict parent

00:04:17.149 --> 00:04:18.950
and the harsher parent.

00:04:18.950 --> 00:04:22.130
And she started looking
at ways she could improve.

00:04:22.130 --> 00:04:25.070
And she actually
started proving to me

00:04:25.070 --> 00:04:27.800
that she could get obedience
and respect without having

00:04:27.800 --> 00:04:29.660
to shout and punish.

00:04:29.660 --> 00:04:32.150
And that's finally, she had--

00:04:32.150 --> 00:04:33.710
I was listening.

00:04:33.710 --> 00:04:35.189
So instead of just
telling me oh,

00:04:35.189 --> 00:04:36.980
here's this parenting
book you should read.

00:04:36.980 --> 00:04:39.146
And I'd tell her oh, please
give me an exact summary

00:04:39.146 --> 00:04:40.310
and show me how it works.

00:04:40.310 --> 00:04:42.770
I don't have time for this.

00:04:42.770 --> 00:04:44.720
Well, finally she
actually did it.

00:04:44.720 --> 00:04:47.050
And she showed me
that-- so she became,

00:04:47.050 --> 00:04:48.680
she actually set better limits.

00:04:48.680 --> 00:04:50.760
She became more consistent.

00:04:50.760 --> 00:04:53.480
And it really changed
the whole family dynamic.

00:04:53.480 --> 00:04:55.670
And so I became interested
in and I became softer.

00:04:55.670 --> 00:04:58.130
And so I started
looking at the research,

00:04:58.130 --> 00:04:59.960
becoming interested
in the subject.

00:04:59.960 --> 00:05:01.880
And I realized
how much parallels

00:05:01.880 --> 00:05:04.340
there were between
leadership and parenting.

00:05:04.340 --> 00:05:07.730
And actually that parenting
skills, like leadership skills

00:05:07.730 --> 00:05:10.682
can be learned and can be honed.

00:05:10.682 --> 00:05:12.890
And that's what I'm going
to talk to you about today.

00:05:15.810 --> 00:05:17.814
So first, let's start
with leadership.

00:05:17.814 --> 00:05:19.480
Obviously there are
so many definitions,

00:05:19.480 --> 00:05:22.130
so I picked one that's
actually quite broad,

00:05:22.130 --> 00:05:26.070
but I think really shows what
we want to do with our children.

00:05:26.070 --> 00:05:28.474
It's from Dwight
Eisenhower and it says,

00:05:28.474 --> 00:05:30.140
leadership is the art
of getting someone

00:05:30.140 --> 00:05:32.240
else to do something
we want done

00:05:32.240 --> 00:05:33.964
because they want to do it.

00:05:33.964 --> 00:05:35.630
Isn't that what we
are trying to achieve

00:05:35.630 --> 00:05:37.274
on a daily basis
with our children?

00:05:37.274 --> 00:05:39.440
Wouldn't it be great if we
had tools to actually get

00:05:39.440 --> 00:05:41.810
them to do things because
they want to do it,

00:05:41.810 --> 00:05:44.464
not because we're telling
them over and over again,

00:05:44.464 --> 00:05:45.380
you've got to do this.

00:05:45.380 --> 00:05:47.810
Please do this, do that,
et cetera, giving them

00:05:47.810 --> 00:05:50.210
orders all day long.

00:05:50.210 --> 00:05:52.340
Well, so that's very
much, actually leadership

00:05:52.340 --> 00:05:54.057
and parenting have
a lot of parallels.

00:05:54.057 --> 00:05:55.640
And what they have
in common, I really

00:05:55.640 --> 00:05:57.560
like this quote from Simon
Sinek, who you probably

00:05:57.560 --> 00:05:58.940
know, author of
"Start With Why",

00:05:58.940 --> 00:06:02.030
it's "Great leaders are able
to inspire people to act.

00:06:02.030 --> 00:06:04.790
Those who are able to
inspire give people

00:06:04.790 --> 00:06:07.520
a sense of purpose
or belonging that

00:06:07.520 --> 00:06:10.220
has little to do with
any external incentive

00:06:10.220 --> 00:06:12.290
or benefit to be gained."

00:06:12.290 --> 00:06:15.430
If you replace the word
leaders with parents, here.

00:06:15.430 --> 00:06:18.209
So great parents are able to
inspire the children to act.

00:06:18.209 --> 00:06:20.000
Those who are able to
inspire give children

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:22.340
a sense of purpose of
belonging that has little

00:06:22.340 --> 00:06:24.800
to do with any
external incentive

00:06:24.800 --> 00:06:26.540
or benefit to be gained.

00:06:26.540 --> 00:06:29.510
And this is really very
much, that's exactly what we

00:06:29.510 --> 00:06:32.270
were saying about moving from
the carrot and stick approach

00:06:32.270 --> 00:06:37.190
to the inspiring and
leading by example.

00:06:37.190 --> 00:06:42.081
Another great quote from
Jack Welch, former CEO of GE

00:06:42.081 --> 00:06:43.580
is "before you are
a leader, success

00:06:43.580 --> 00:06:44.720
is all about growing yourself.

00:06:44.720 --> 00:06:46.095
When you become
a leader, success

00:06:46.095 --> 00:06:47.690
is all about growing others."

00:06:47.690 --> 00:06:50.240
Again, if you replace the word
leaders with parents here,

00:06:50.240 --> 00:06:52.010
is before you are
a parent, success

00:06:52.010 --> 00:06:53.260
is all about growing yourself.

00:06:53.260 --> 00:06:55.127
But when you become
a parent, success

00:06:55.127 --> 00:06:56.710
is really about
growing your children.

00:06:59.390 --> 00:07:02.540
So the last quotes
I'm going to show

00:07:02.540 --> 00:07:05.840
you are about why leadership is
actually here, in this sense,

00:07:05.840 --> 00:07:07.520
is different from management.

00:07:07.520 --> 00:07:09.630
So because I spoke
about management by fear

00:07:09.630 --> 00:07:12.380
and that's exactly, we want
to replace it with leadership.

00:07:12.380 --> 00:07:14.580
And so management is about
arranging and telling,

00:07:14.580 --> 00:07:19.000
while leadership is about
nurturing and enhancing.

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:20.935
And as Klaus Balkenhol,
Olympic champion

00:07:20.935 --> 00:07:23.060
said, "there is a difference
between being a leader

00:07:23.060 --> 00:07:24.350
and being a boss.

00:07:24.350 --> 00:07:26.530
Both are based on authority.

00:07:26.530 --> 00:07:28.730
A boss demands blind
obedience, while a leader

00:07:28.730 --> 00:07:33.910
earns his authority through
understanding and trust."

00:07:33.910 --> 00:07:37.510
So why don't we give a
go at actually defining

00:07:37.510 --> 00:07:40.190
what the key leadership skills.

00:07:40.190 --> 00:07:43.030
What have you experienced,
either as a manager--

00:07:43.030 --> 00:07:45.700
and actually something that's
worked really well for you

00:07:45.700 --> 00:07:47.290
in inspiring your teams.

00:07:47.290 --> 00:07:49.420
Or if you've been
basically, you've

00:07:49.420 --> 00:07:51.880
had managers and leaders who
have really inspired you,

00:07:51.880 --> 00:07:53.380
what are the key
things that they've

00:07:53.380 --> 00:07:56.980
done well that you remember?

