they're like oh my god,
there are so many rules.

00:46:41.780 --> 00:46:42.730
I can't bear all this.

00:46:42.730 --> 00:46:46.100
So as long as you give
enough control and autonomy,

00:46:46.100 --> 00:46:48.830
children will actually learn
to make mistakes and it's fine,

00:46:48.830 --> 00:46:50.719
but there are
consequences to this.

00:46:50.719 --> 00:46:53.010
So they learn that there are
consequences for mistakes.

00:46:53.010 --> 00:46:55.354
It's not big punishment
and oh, horrible.

00:46:55.354 --> 00:46:57.770
It's actually, the idea is not
to make children feel worse

00:46:57.770 --> 00:46:59.020
in order to do better.

00:46:59.020 --> 00:47:01.040
It's for them to
always feel good

00:47:01.040 --> 00:47:05.770
and to want to be in this family
and want to do things correctly

00:47:05.770 --> 00:47:08.169
because they see that
otherwise, you know,

00:47:08.169 --> 00:47:09.710
my parents are not
going to be happy.

00:47:09.710 --> 00:47:13.825
Or it's not actually counter to
the way the family functions.

00:47:13.825 --> 00:47:15.200
So hopefully it's
that, you know,

00:47:15.200 --> 00:47:16.940
it's for you to decide
how many exceptions you're

00:47:16.940 --> 00:47:17.523
going to make.

00:47:17.523 --> 00:47:19.490
But if you make too
many, then you're

00:47:19.490 --> 00:47:21.065
letting them run
the show and not

00:47:21.065 --> 00:47:22.940
realize there is a
consequence and that there

00:47:22.940 --> 00:47:26.540
are rules while you want
to teach them the rules.

00:47:26.540 --> 00:47:29.810
AUDIENCE: So sometimes breaking
rules or at least perceived

00:47:29.810 --> 00:47:31.640
rules can be a good thing.

00:47:34.580 --> 00:47:37.420
Are you concerned or
is there any evidence

00:47:37.420 --> 00:47:40.082
to show or counter
evidence that you're

00:47:40.082 --> 00:47:41.540
going to end up
raising a child who

00:47:41.540 --> 00:47:45.490
isn't capable of breaking rules
when we see rules as an adult?

00:47:45.490 --> 00:47:50.800
Because I want my son to be
able to break rules sometimes.

00:47:50.800 --> 00:47:52.610
NADIM SAAD: Totally,
again, it's--

00:47:52.610 --> 00:47:56.420
I mean, it's a similar
question and I understand that.

00:47:56.420 --> 00:47:59.150
And it's funny because I rarely
get these kind of questions.

00:47:59.150 --> 00:48:01.320
And clearly Google
is very much, it

00:48:01.320 --> 00:48:02.570
is part of the Google culture.

00:48:02.570 --> 00:48:03.611
And I think that's great.

00:48:03.611 --> 00:48:06.110
I think it's, you
know, you want to be--

00:48:06.110 --> 00:48:10.370
to question, you know, the
rules and then otherwise you

00:48:10.370 --> 00:48:12.846
can't actually create a lot.

00:48:12.846 --> 00:48:14.720
I think it's about
finding this right balance

00:48:14.720 --> 00:48:15.553
as I was explaining.

00:48:15.553 --> 00:48:20.000
But really it's offering
a lot of autonomy

00:48:20.000 --> 00:48:22.880
and a lot of opportunities
to do things differently

00:48:22.880 --> 00:48:25.190
and to decide what
the rules are.

00:48:25.190 --> 00:48:29.030
So for example, in the
problem solving session,

00:48:29.030 --> 00:48:31.700
you're not imposing your
rule on your children.

00:48:31.700 --> 00:48:33.800
You're telling them,
OK, that's what we

00:48:33.800 --> 00:48:36.650
want as an outcome as a family.

00:48:36.650 --> 00:48:39.947
So what are the right rules
for our family to achieve this?

00:48:39.947 --> 00:48:41.780
And sometimes you'll
go against your feeling

00:48:41.780 --> 00:48:43.560
like, oh my god, really?

00:48:43.560 --> 00:48:44.570
But you'll go with it.

00:48:44.570 --> 00:48:45.950
And you'll just
go, you know, OK.

00:48:45.950 --> 00:48:48.830
I mean, I don't really
agree but I'll go with that.

00:48:48.830 --> 00:48:51.020
That in itself is
kind of a way to teach

00:48:51.020 --> 00:48:53.744
them to think differently,
to think outside of the box,

00:48:53.744 --> 00:48:55.160
and to find solutions
to problems.

00:48:55.160 --> 00:48:57.670
I think that's what
we want to achieve.

00:48:57.670 --> 00:48:59.300
Just breaking the
rules for the sake

00:48:59.300 --> 00:49:04.670
of breaking them is kind of
goes, it will go against you.

00:49:04.670 --> 00:49:06.650
And sometimes, and
it's fine, they

00:49:06.650 --> 00:49:08.240
have to make
mistakes by the way.

00:49:08.240 --> 00:49:09.980
So it's not like
that we're going

00:49:09.980 --> 00:49:12.316
to create these perfect kids
who never break the rules.

00:49:12.316 --> 00:49:13.940
It's just when they
break them, instead

00:49:13.940 --> 00:49:15.773
of getting angry and
thinking, oh my god how

00:49:15.773 --> 00:49:19.240
dare you do that, it's
actually oh, so sad.

00:49:19.240 --> 00:49:20.910
You know what the rules are.

00:49:20.910 --> 00:49:21.830
So that's a mistake.

00:49:21.830 --> 00:49:24.950
It's OK and that's the
consequence that you agreed on.

00:49:24.950 --> 00:49:27.494
And then instead of going
no, that's not fair.

00:49:27.494 --> 00:49:29.660
They'll go, yeah, I mean I
decided this consequence.

00:49:29.660 --> 00:49:30.340
It's fine.

00:49:30.340 --> 00:49:31.590
You know, and it's tough.

00:49:31.590 --> 00:49:34.910
It can be tough, but it's fine.

00:49:34.910 --> 00:49:36.139
I hope that answers.

00:49:36.139 --> 00:49:37.680
AUDIENCE: Right,
thanks for the talk.

00:49:37.680 --> 00:49:40.615
My kids are 8 and 12 and
we have some routines

00:49:40.615 --> 00:49:42.270
that work quite well for us.

00:49:42.270 --> 00:49:45.205
But then we have some which have
been really non established,

00:49:45.205 --> 00:49:47.300
and which we would like
to change because they

00:49:47.300 --> 00:49:49.300
don't necessarily work out now.

00:49:49.300 --> 00:49:51.260
So for example, we
used to always get

00:49:51.260 --> 00:49:53.420
into do some kind of
practice after dinner.

00:49:53.420 --> 00:49:56.380
But we find these days that
perhaps everybody's a bit tired

00:49:56.380 --> 00:49:58.837
then and piano practice can
get a bit confrontational.

00:49:58.837 --> 00:50:00.920
And we'd like to bring it
earlier in the day maybe

00:50:00.920 --> 00:50:04.135
before dinner and say then
we're met with big resistance.

00:50:04.135 --> 00:50:07.060
I wonder if you have tips on
how to kind of deal with that.

00:50:07.060 --> 00:50:10.060
NADIM SAAD: So is there
resistance because they just

00:50:10.060 --> 00:50:11.910
want to have fun
before and that they

00:50:11.910 --> 00:50:14.350
are used to doing it after
or where does it come from?

00:50:14.350 --> 00:50:16.308
AUDIENCE: Because in
their mind, piano practice

00:50:16.308 --> 00:50:17.914
is always after dinner

00:50:17.914 --> 00:50:19.080
NADIM SAAD: OK, so there's--

00:50:19.080 --> 00:50:19.520
AUDIENCE: At least
that's what's voiced.

00:50:19.520 --> 00:50:21.020
I mean maybe there's
something else.

00:50:21.020 --> 00:50:23.740
But yeah, that's the
objection that we're given.

00:50:23.740 --> 00:50:26.030
NADIM SAAD: Yeah,
well this is very--

00:50:26.030 --> 00:50:29.210
usually that's very much the
purpose of a family meeting.

00:50:29.210 --> 00:50:32.900
Is when it's outside of this
kind of resistance already,

00:50:32.900 --> 00:50:34.360
you should do it before.

00:50:34.360 --> 00:50:37.190
But you can agree on
why it's better for them

00:50:37.190 --> 00:50:38.392
to do it earlier.

00:50:38.392 --> 00:50:40.850
I mean that's where usually,
when you get-- you get buy in.

00:50:40.850 --> 00:50:42.300
It's like any meeting.

00:50:42.300 --> 00:50:45.260
To get buy in, they mustn't
be in resistant mode.

00:50:45.260 --> 00:50:48.260
They have to realize
what the intention is

00:50:48.260 --> 00:50:49.914
and why it's better.

00:50:49.914 --> 00:50:51.830
And or otherwise you say
well, the consequence

00:50:51.830 --> 00:50:54.020
could be well you have
to have dinner earlier

00:50:54.020 --> 00:50:56.040
and maybe then we can't
participate in dinner.

00:50:56.040 --> 00:50:58.665
I mean things-- you can actually
make things up so that to make

00:50:58.665 --> 00:51:00.250
sure that--

00:51:00.250 --> 00:51:02.550
I mean it's not, it's
just showing them

00:51:02.550 --> 00:51:05.310
the consequence of
not going that way

00:51:05.310 --> 00:51:07.352
without it being a battle.

00:51:07.352 --> 00:51:09.810
Because that's what you want
to remove and everything we do

00:51:09.810 --> 00:51:10.500
is remove those.

00:51:10.500 --> 00:51:13.700
This battle, these positions,
that it's a win-lose situation.

00:51:13.700 --> 00:51:15.649
Actually everything is
a win-win situation.

00:51:15.649 --> 00:51:17.190
I mean we're doing
this for our kids.

00:51:17.190 --> 00:51:19.080
So they have to realize it.

00:51:19.080 --> 00:51:21.850
And the more you create this
environment of shared purpose

00:51:21.850 --> 00:51:23.800
and we have the
same goals, the more

00:51:23.800 --> 00:51:25.800
you can achieve no
resistance to piano practice.

00:51:25.800 --> 00:51:28.050
Actually yeah, it's true
actually, I'm going to do it.

00:51:28.050 --> 00:51:31.530
Invent, I mean do it, be
creative, that's what I mean.

00:51:31.530 --> 00:51:35.760
And they're going to be your
best creative, you know,

00:51:35.760 --> 00:51:37.780
they're going to bring
the best creative ideas.

00:51:37.780 --> 00:51:40.071
So allow them to have these
ideas because maybe they'll

00:51:40.071 --> 00:51:42.050
come up with something
that works for you,

00:51:42.050 --> 00:51:44.340
and that you didn't
even think about.

00:51:44.340 --> 00:51:45.870
So to have these conversations.

